Toward the end of Dec., 51 B.C., Cicero was in Tarsus and sent thence official letters to the consuls asking for a supplicatio,³ accompanied by a letter of similar purport to Cato, the senatorial leaders* The senate voted the supplicatiof and, turning over his province to the quaestor Caelius Caldus, on July 30, Cicero set out on his homeward journey in high hopes of a triumph. There is no more honorable period in Cicero's life than that of his pro-

by his wife Terentia.⁸ After a delay of several weeks at -
